Problem:- Sliding Window Maximum
Hard
Topics
premium lock icon
Companies
Hint
You are given an array of integers nums, there is a sliding window of size k which is moving from the very left of the array to the very right. You can only see the k numbers in the window. Each time the sliding window moves right by one position.

Return the max sliding window.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], k = 3
Output: [3,3,5,5,6,7]
Explanation: 
Window position                Max
---------------               -----
[1  3  -1] -3  5  3  6  7       3
 1 [3  -1  -3] 5  3  6  7       3
 1  3 [-1  -3  5] 3  6  7       5
 1  3  -1 [-3  5  3] 6  7       5
 1  3  -1  -3 [5  3  6] 7       6
 1  3  -1  -3  5 [3  6  7]      7

Solutions:-

LeetCode 239: Sliding Window Maximum computes max for every contiguous window of size k. Deque monotonic queue O(n) solution.

#Java Implementation (Monotonic Deque)

class Solution {
    public int[] maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k) {
        Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();  // Indices, decreasing order
        int[] result = new int[nums.length - k + 1];
        
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            // Remove indices out of current window
            while (!dq.isEmpty() && dq.peekFirst() <= i - k) {
                dq.pollFirst();
            }
            
            // Remove indices with smaller values (won't be max)
            while (!dq.isEmpty() && nums[dq.peekLast()] < nums[i]) {
                dq.pollLast();
            }
            
            dq.offerLast(i);
            
            // First window result
            if (i >= k - 1) {
                result[i - k + 1] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];
            }
        }
        
        return result;
    }
}

Deque: Stores indices in decreasing value order. Front = max.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Deque: Indices of useful candidates (decreasing nums values)
For each i:
Clean front: Remove out-of-window (i-k)
Clean back: Remove smaller values (nums[dq.back] < nums[i])
Add i: dq.offerLast(i)
i ≥ k-1: result[i-k+1] = nums[dq.peekFirst()]
Result: Max for each window
Trace: [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], k=3

text
i=0: dq=[0]
i=1: remove 1<3, dq=[1] (3)
i=2: dq=[1,2], result[0]=3
i=3: remove i=1(3> -3), dq=[2,3]
i=4: remove 5>-1,-3, dq=[4] (5), result[2]=5
... Final: [3,3,5,5,6,7]

#Thought Process
Brute O(nk): Max each window → TLE.
Monotonic deque genius:

text
Maintain decreasing candidates
Front = current max (O(1) access)
Smaller values can't become max later → discard!
Each index: Added/removed once → O(n)

#Edge Cases
k=1: Each element is max
k=n: Single window max
All decreasing: Deque keeps all until expire
Duplicates: Handle equal values
